===Former buildings===
The [[Robert B. Atwood Building]] in [[Anchorage, Alaska]], was at one time named the Bank of America Center, renamed in conjunction with the bank's acquisition of building tenant Security Pacific Bank. This particular branch was later acquired by Alaska-based Northrim Bank and moved across the street to the [[Linny Pacillo Parking Garage]].

The [[Bank of America Building (Providence)]] opened in 1928 as the Industrial Trust Building and remains the tallest building in Rhode Island. Through a number of mergers, it was later known as the Industrial National Bank building and the Fleet Bank building. The building was leased by Bank of America from 2004 to 2012 and has been vacant since March 2013. The building is commonly known as the Superman Building based on a popular belief that it was the model for the [[Daily Planet]] building in the [[Superman]] comic books.

The [[Miami Tower]] iconic in its appearance in ''[[Miami Vice]]'' was known as the Bank of America Tower for many years. It is located in [[Greater Downtown Miami|Downtown Miami]]. On April 18, 2012, the AIA's Florida Chapter placed it on its list of Florida Architecture: 100 Years. 100 Places as the Bank of America Tower.<ref>{{cite web |title=Florida Architecture: 100 Years. 100 Places |publisher=AIA Florida |url=http://aiaflatop100.org/buildings.cfm |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505184939/http://aiaflatop100.org/buildings.cfm |archive-date=May 5, 2012}}</ref>

[[TC Energy Center]] in Houston, Texas, was previously known as Bank of America Center until Bank of America ended its tenancy in the building in June 2019. Designed in the [[postmodern architecture]] style by renowned architect [[Philip Johnson]], the building has been one of the most iconic and recognizable landmarks of the downtown Houston skyline since it was completed in 1983.<ref>{{cite web |date=2019-10-15 |title=Iconic downtown Houston office tower renamed TC Energy Center |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/business/prime-property/article/Iconic-downtown-Houston-office-tower-renamed-TC-14521396.php |access-date=2021-01-08 |website=HoustonChronicle.com |language=en-US |archive-date=January 9, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210109145001/https://www.houstonchronicle.com/business/prime-property/article/Iconic-downtown-Houston-office-tower-renamed-TC-14521396.php |url-status=live }}</ref>

